Reissner-Nordstrom black holes 

The numerical behaviour of the first few overtones of a RN black hole
was studied numerically by Andersson and Onozawa, who
unveiled a very peculiar behaviour as the modes' imaginary part
increases. Our numerical codes are in excellent agreement with their
results. In comparing with their paper note, however, that Andersson
and Onozawa count modes starting from , while we label the
fundamental mode by , following Leaver (see table 1 in
). The results we display refer to perturbations reducing to
pure gravitational perturbations of Schwarzschild in the uncharged
limit. The trajectories described by the modes in the complex-
plane first show "closed loops", as in the top left panel of figure
. Then they get a spiral-like shape, moving out of their
Schwarzschild value and "looping in" towards some limiting frequency
as  tends to the extremal value. This kind of behaviour is shown in
the top right panel of figure . We have observed that such a
spiralling behaviour sets in for larger values of the modes' imaginary
part (i.e., larger values of ) as the angular index 
increases. In other words, increasing  for a given value of the
mode index  has the effect of "unwinding" the spirals, as can be
observed in the two panels in the second row of figure
. However, for each  the spiralling behaviour is
eventually observed when  is large enough; a typical example for
 is shown in the last plot of figure .

Maybe a clearer picture of the modes' behaviour can be obtained
looking separately at the real and imaginary parts of the mode
frequencies as function of charge. Let us focus first on the real
parts. The corresponding numerical results are shown in figure
, together with the predictions of the analytic formula
().  It's quite apparent that, as the mode order grows, the
oscillating behaviour as a function of charge start earlier and
earlier. As  increases, the oscillations become faster, the
convergence of the continued fraction method slower, and the required
computing time gets longer. Therefore, when the imaginary part
increases it becomes more difficult to follow the roots numerically as
we approach the extremal value . That's why our data for large
values of  do not cover the whole range of allowed values for
. Despite these difficulties, we have many reasons to trust our
numerics. We have carefully checked our results, using first double
and then quadrupole precision in our Fortran codes (indeed, as 
increases, we can obtain results for large values of the charge only
using quadrupole precision). As we have shown earlier, our frequencies
accurately reproduce Nollert's results in the Schwarzschild limit, so
our numerics can be trusted for small values of .  Furthermore, the
predictions of the analytic formula exactly overlap with the
oscillations we observe for large values of the charge. Not only this
does give support to the asymptotic formula; it also gives
us faith that the numerics are meaningful also for large charge, where
we don't have any published results to confirm our predictions.

Similar considerations apply to the imaginary parts. We present a few
plots illustrating the general trend for the imaginary parts in figure
, showing again excellent agreement with the asymptotic
formula () as  increases. Once again, the analytic formula
shows deviations from our "exact" numerical results only for small
values of the charge, probably indicating that corrections of order
 should be taken into account for small values of . When
we look at the mode trajectories in the complex- plane, the
increasingly oscillating behaviour of the real and imaginary parts
means that the number of "spirals" described by the mode before
reaching the extremal value increases roughly as the mode order .

Can we deduce something from the agreement of our numerical results
with formula () at large values of the charge?  It would be
extremely interesting to draw consequences on the extremal RN case,
for various reasons. First of all, the QNM spectrum for extremal RN
black holes is characterized by an isospectrality between
electromagnetic and gravitational perturbations, which has been
motivated in as a manifestation of supersymmetry.
Furthermore, topological arguments have been used to show that the
entropy-area relation breaks down for extreme QNM's
. Therefore, we believe that some caution is required in
claiming that the connection between QNM's and the area spectrum is
still valid for extreme black holes, as recently advocated in
.  These problems may be connected with our recent finding
that extremally charged black holes in a (non-asymptotically flat)
anti-de Sitter spacetime could be marginally unstable.

Our numerics seem to indicate that we can trust formula () in
the large-charge regime. Then a very interesting conclusion follows
: the real part of the frequency for extremal RN black holes
coincides with the Schwarzschild value, i.e.
XRN 
_R^RN 34  as  Q1/2.
However, it is quite difficult to check this prediction numerically.
In the extremal RN case, due to the coalescence of the inner and outer
horizons, the singularity structure of the radial perturbation
equations changes. Therefore one has to apply a different (and
slightly more involved) procedure, which has been described in
. We have tried to apply that procedure to get highly
damped QNM's. Apparently, the extremal RN QNM's show a behaviour which
is rather similar to that of Schwarzschild QNM's (see, e.g., figure 1
in): they have finite real part for small values of
, approach the pure-imaginary axis as  is
increased, and then the real part increases again. This would support
the predictions of the asymptotic formula (). Unfortunately,
we have not yet managed to get stable numerical results for large
values of . We plan to improve our codes and obtain more
numerically stable results in the future.  

If, supported by the agreement between our numerics and the analytical
prediction, we assume that formula () holds, an extremely
interesting result emerges: Hod's conjecture () is incompatible  with the first law of black hole mechanics (),
which predicts that the real part of the asymptotic frequencies in the
extremal case should be zero. Is this related to the failure of the
area-entropy relation in the extremal case, or does it simply imply
that Hod's conjecture is wrong, at least for extremal black holes?

Kerr black holes 

Quasinormal frequencies of Kerr black holes were first studied by
Leaver using continued fraction techniques and subsequently
investigated by other authors.  

A systematic exploration of the behaviour of the first few overtones
was carried out only some years ago, using Leaver's continued fraction
method, by Onozawa, who found some rather odd features as the
mode damping increases. For example, Detweiler showed that
the first few modes having  have vanishing imaginary part and
real part equal to  as the black hole becomes extremal (in our
units, as ). He also showed analytically that there can be
infinite solutions to the Teukolsky equation having  and
, which led to the suspicion that all  modes having
 should "cluster" on the real axis at  as the black
hole becomes extremal.  An interesting outcome of Onozawa's
investigation was that, for given values of  and , there is
at least one mode frequency which does not tend to  in the
extremal limit.  Onozawa also found that, when , modes
having negative  (which for the first few overtones show a tendency
to decrease in frequency as the hole is spun up) show instead a
tendency to "turn around" and increase their frequency as 
increases, sometimes showing strange "loops" in the complex-
plane (see figures 3 and 4 in).

We have confirmed Onozawa's results, and extended them to moderately
high . However, since one has to solve simultaneously the angular
and the radial continued fraction, the numerical problem turned out to
be much more tricky than the search of highly-damped modes in the RN
case. Comparing Nollert's technique and a standard summation of the
continued fraction using Gautschi's algorithm, we found out
that it is much harder to achieve a stable numerical computation of
modes for  or higher. Because of these
convergence problems, even using Nollert's method, we did not manage
to push the numerical calculation to very large values of
. However, even moderately high values of  shed some light on
what should be the asymptotic behaviour of Kerr QNM's.

Let us first consider Kerr perturbations having . We have been
able to compute quite a few moderately highly damped modes for 
and , and in figure  we show two of these modes. These
plots should be compared to the RN modes we have shown in figure
: there is a similar "looping" behaviour, with the number
of loops increasing as the damping of the mode increases. We notice
that a similar looping behaviour has recently been found by
Glampedakis and Andersson for scalar  perturbations of Kerr black
holes, using a different method. Figure  and
 show the real and imaginary parts (respectively) of some
Kerr modes with . It is useful to compare these plots with
figures  and : the behaviour is extremely
similar, and asymptotically it can probably be described by some
formula reminiscent of (). Of course, such a behaviour is not
even close to that predicted by formula ().

Hod recently used Onozawa's data, which to our knowledge are the only
available published data for highly damped Kerr modes, to show that
the results predicted by formula () agree with the
numerically computations in within , at least when
. We repeated Onozawa's calculations, finding excellent agreement
with his results, and then extended it to higher-order modes. We found
that, as  increases, the formula conjectured by Hod does not seem
to provide a good fit to the asymptotic modes. As shown in figure
, the proposed formula disagrees quite badly in the small
rotation rate regime even for the low-lying modes which were used for
comparison by Hod. In any event, this is to be expected and does not
contradict Hod's claim, since it is known from previous calculations
in the Schwarzschild limit that modes with  have real
parts of the QNM frequencies which are not close enough to their
asymptotic value. However, if formula () really holds in
the asymptotic limit, one would expect the agreement with numerical
calculations to get better as the mode's imaginary part increases; on
the contrary, figure  shows that, as  increases, the
agreement gets worse, even for large rotation rates (which used to
show rather good agreement for ). So Hod's formula does not
seem to provide an accurate fit to the asymptotic frequencies. We
actually found that, as the mode order increase, modes having 
are fitted extremely well (relative errors being of order 
 when ) by the relation
