The convergence to this value as  increases is faster for large
values of , and generally the agreement between formula ()
and our numerics is good for values of .

Preliminary calculations show that modes having  and ,
 and  show a more complicated behaviour. We are currently
trying to improve our understanding of highly damped Kerr QNM's using
both analytical and numerical techniques.

Conclusions 

In this paper we have numerically investigated the asymptotic
behaviour of QNM's for charged (RN) and rotating (Kerr) black holes.
We have first confirmed Nollert's results and extended them to scalar
perturbations of Schwarzschild black holes. Our numerics are
consistent with
_R=34 +k_s[(s^2-1)-3l(l+1)] n  ,
where, within our accuracy, . Recently the
constant  has been determined analytically - see formula
() - and our result may be useful to determine  as well.

More importantly, our results for charged and rotating black holes do
not agree with the simple behaviour predicted by Hod's conjecture for
the real part of the frequency, as given in formula ().  We
have shown that both the real and the imaginary part of RN QNM's as
functions of charge display an oscillating behaviour. The oscillations
start at smaller values of the charge and get faster as 
increases. We have compared our numerical results to the predictions
of the asymptotic formula () derived in and found
that, in general, they agree extremely well, especially for large
values of the mode index . The formula derived by Motl and Neitzke
only fails to reproduce our numerical results in the limit of small
charge.  Quite likely, their expression has a wrong limit in the
Schwarzschild case (the real part tending to  instead of
) because finite- corrections become relevant as 
tends to zero. A computation of higher-order corrections to
the asymptotic RN formula will probably give a final answer on the
reasons for the small- discrepancy we observe. If we trust the
predictions of formula (), as the agreement between
analytical and numerical results suggests to do, the asymptotic
frequency for extremal RN black holes is the same as for Schwarzschild
black holes. This implies that for extremal RN black holes, Hod's
proposal to apply Bohr's correspondence principle is incompatible with
the first law of black hole mechanics . It remains to be decided
whether this is due to the failure of the area-entropy relation in
that limit, or to Hod's proposal being wrong (at least in
the extremal RN case).

Highly damped gravitational quasinormal frequencies of rotating (Kerr)
black holes proved more difficult to compute, even using Nollert's
method, and show a more complicated behaviour. For , we observe
spirals in the complex plane reminiscent of RN modes, confirming the
behaviour found in for highly damped scalar 
perturbations. For , the behaviour is completely
different. Modes seem to approach an asymptotic frequency
, where  is the angular velocity of the
black hole horizon.  The convergence to the limiting value is slower
as  decreases. We think that a calculation of finite-
corrections to the asymptotics may help explain this different
convergence rate. A more extensive investigation of asymptotic Kerr
QNM's is ongoing.

